🔹 Practical 6: GPS Module Interfacing with Raspberry Pi
1️⃣ Objective

To interface a GPS module with Raspberry Pi and obtain geographical coordinates (latitude and longitude).

2️⃣ Concept Overview

GPS (Global Positioning System) uses satellites to determine location.

System flow:

GPS Satellites
      ↓
GPS Module
      ↓
Raspberry Pi (UART Serial Communication)
      ↓
Location Data (Latitude, Longitude, Time)

This technology is used in:

Vehicle tracking

Delivery logistics

Smart agriculture

Navigation systems

3️⃣ Components Required
Component	Quantity
Raspberry Pi	1
GPS Module (Neo-6M commonly used)	1
Jumper wires	Few
Breadboard	Optional
Internet not required	—
4️⃣ GPS Module Overview

Common module: Neo-6M GPS

Features:

✔ 50 tracking channels
✔ Accuracy ~2.5 meters
✔ UART communication
✔ Built-in antenna

The GPS module receives signals from multiple satellites and calculates position.

5️⃣ Communication Method

GPS communicates using:

UART Serial Communication

Typical speed:

9600 baud rate
6️⃣ Circuit Connection
GPS Module	Raspberry Pi
VCC	5V
GND	GND
TX	GPIO15 (RX)
RX	GPIO14 (TX)

⚠ Important:

TX of GPS → RX of Pi
RX of GPS → TX of Pi

7️⃣ Enable Serial Interface

Open terminal:

sudo raspi-config

Go to:

Interface Options → Serial

Disable login shell
Enable hardware serial

Reboot:

sudo reboot
8️⃣ Install Required Libraries

Install GPS parsing library:

pip3 install pynmea2
9️⃣ Understanding GPS Data (NMEA Format)

GPS sends data in NMEA sentences.

Example:

$GPGGA,123519,4807.038,N,01131.000,E,1,08,0.9,545.4,M,46.9,M,,*47

Important fields:

Field	Meaning
Latitude	Position north/south
Longitude	Position east/west
Time	UTC time
Satellites	Number of satellites used
🔟 Python Code – Read GPS Coordinates

Create file:

nano gps_read.py

Code:

import serial
import pynmea2

port = "/dev/ttyS0"

ser = serial.Serial(port, baudrate=9600, timeout=0.5)

while True:
    data = ser.readline().decode('ascii', errors='replace')

    if data.startswith('$GPGGA'):
        msg = pynmea2.parse(data)

        print("Latitude:", msg.latitude)
        print("Longitude:", msg.longitude)
        print("Satellites:", msg.num_sats)
        print("-------------------")
1️⃣1️⃣ Run the Program
python3 gps_read.py

Output example:

Latitude: 19.2183
Longitude: 72.9781
Satellites: 7

You will see coordinates updating continuously.

1️⃣2️⃣ How It Works

Step-by-step:

1️⃣ GPS module receives signals from satellites
2️⃣ Calculates distance from each satellite
3️⃣ Determines position using triangulation
4️⃣ Sends location data to Raspberry Pi
5️⃣ Python program reads and displays coordinates

