🔹 Practical 7: IoT Web Controlled Home Automation using Raspberry Pi
1️⃣ Objective

To control home appliances (like lights or fan) using a web interface hosted on Raspberry Pi.

2️⃣ Concept Overview

Instead of using a physical switch:

User → Web Page → Raspberry Pi Server → Relay → Appliance

System architecture:

User (Mobile / Laptop Browser)
            ↓
     Web Interface
            ↓
     Raspberry Pi Server
            ↓
        GPIO Control
            ↓
      Relay Module
            ↓
        Appliance

This is a basic IoT automation system.

3️⃣ Components Required
Component	Quantity
Raspberry Pi	1
Relay Module (1 or 2 channel)	1
LED / Bulb / Fan	1
Jumper wires	Few
Breadboard	Optional
WiFi / LAN connection	Required

⚠ In lab, usually LED is used instead of high voltage devices for safety.

4️⃣ Relay Module Overview

Relay works like an electronic switch.

Control logic:

GPIO HIGH → Relay ON → Device ON
GPIO LOW → Relay OFF → Device OFF

Relay allows Raspberry Pi (3.3V logic) to control high voltage appliances.

5️⃣ Circuit Connection
Relay Pin	Raspberry Pi
VCC	5V
GND	GND
IN1	GPIO17

If using LED instead of relay:

GPIO17 → Resistor → LED → GND

6️⃣ Install Required Libraries

We will use Flask web server.

Install:

pip3 install flask
7️⃣ Create Project Folder
mkdir home_automation
cd home_automation
8️⃣ Python Code (Flask Web Server)

Create file:

nano app.py

Code:

from flask import Flask, render_template
import RPi.GPIO as GPIO

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)

relay = 17
GPIO.setup(relay, GPIO.OUT)

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return render_template('index.html')

@app.route('/on')
def turn_on():
    GPIO.output(relay, True)
    return render_template('index.html')

@app.route('/off')
def turn_off():
    GPIO.output(relay, False)
    return render_template('index.html')

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)
9️⃣ Create Web Page

Create folder:

mkdir templates

Create file:

nano templates/index.html

Code:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Home Automation</title>
</head>

<body>

<h2>Raspberry Pi Home Automation</h2>

<a href="/on">
<button style="width:100px;height:50px;">ON</button>
</a>

<a href="/off">
<button style="width:100px;height:50px;">OFF</button>
</a>

</body>
</html>
🔟 Run the Web Server

Run program:

python3 app.py

Terminal will show:

Running on http://0.0.0.0:5000
1️⃣1️⃣ Access Web Interface

Open browser in same network.

Type:

http://RASPBERRY_PI_IP:5000

Example:

http://192.168.1.20:5000

You will see:

Home Automation

[ ON ]   [ OFF ]

Click buttons → Device turns ON/OFF.

1️⃣2️⃣ How It Works

Step-by-step:

1️⃣ Browser sends request to Raspberry Pi
2️⃣ Flask web server receives request
3️⃣ Python program executes GPIO command
4️⃣ Relay switches device
5️⃣ Web page reloads

1️⃣3️⃣ Algorithm

Initialize GPIO pins

Start Flask web server

Create routes for ON and OFF commands

Receive user request from browser

Execute GPIO control

Update web page

